abstract: One subject for speculative gossip was eliminated by the declaration of the regular dividend on Anaconda. This was not unexpected, and when the stock was strong last week it was taken as conclusive evidence that no change would be made in the dividend. There remains, however, the Atchison dividend, which will be considered to-day, and which, it is freely predicted, will be reduced.

abstract: WASHINGTON, March 31. -- The investigation started by Representative George L. Lilley of Connecticut, who charged the Electric Boat Company with using improper methods to influence Congress, made a volte face to-day, reversing the positions of defendants and prosecutors. abstract: William J. Bryan will not attend the Jefferson Day dinner of the National Democratic Club, to be held at the Hotel Knickerbocker on April 13. abstract: SAN DIEGO, Cal., April 1. -- The battleship Connecticut, flagship of the Atlantic fleet, with Rear Admiral Evans on board, arrived from Magdalena Bay at 5 o'clock this morning. Admiral Evans left this afternoon for San Louis Obispo, where he will take treatment for rheumatism, which has afflicted him since the fleet arrived at Rio de Janeiro. The Admiral expects to rejoin the fleet at Santa Cruz on May 1.

abstract: The Committee on Finance and Currency of the Chamber of Commerce made public yesterday the report on the currency measures now before Congress which will be submitted to the Chamber at its meeting to-day. Both the Aldrich bill and the Fowler bill, the committee states, are distinctly at variance with the principles approved by the Chamber, and are so antagonistic to each other that comprehensive legislation at an early date is improbable.

abstract: The disappearance of the papers in the Alfred G. Vanderbilt divorce suit was explained yesterday morning at the County Clerk's office when one of the clerks announced that he had found them lying underneath a desk. abstract: TERRE HAUTE, Ind., April 2. -- Just after a jury late this afternoon had returned a verdict finding Henry F. McDonald guilty of dynamiting a church and two stores at Sanford, the convicted man drew a pistol and opened fire. He killed Chief of Detectives William E. Dwyer and wounded five others, McDonald himself fell in the courtroom battle that followed wounded by a dozen bullets from the officers' pistols, but still living.

abstract: The proof that among the millions of New Yorkers there was one capable of throwing a bomb at the police is accompanied by reassuring proofs of compensating facts. abstract: WASHINGTON, April 3. -- Baron Rosen, the Russian Ambassador, was in conference with Secretary Root at the State Department to-day. abstract: WASHINGTON, April 3. -- An accident marred the fifth race at Benning to-day. Woodline stumbled just after turning into the stretch and threw his jockey, Krause. The youngster was badly shaken up, but not apparently seriously hurt. Millstone won the race handily, with Umbrella second and Venus third. In the sixth event Park Row repeated his good race of a few days ago and won, ridden out, with Killiecrankie second, and the favorite, Poquessing, third.

abstract: IN the opinion of Dr. Edwin R.A. Seligman, Professor of Political Economy at Columbia, anarchy is the inevitable result of the present social conditions, and is due to a combination of misfortune and ignorance. He does not believe it to be possible to stamp anarchy out by force, but he does believe that there are ways by which society can lessen misfortune and ignorance, and in doing so lessen the trend to anarchy.

abstract: TULARE, Cal., April 4. -- We are in California in the good De Dion car. Yesterday everything was sand or rock, all yellow or black, except the blue of heaven, and to-day, by a miracle, we arise in the middle of green plains and of trees with leaves. The telegraph poles are made of the costly eucalyptus, the mountains are far away on our right, and we can see only their tops covered with snow.

abstract: The autograph journal of Thomas Rodney, member of the Continental Congress and Colonel of Delaware troops in the Revolutionary War, will come under the auctioneer's hammer this week. It is full of interesting historical statements relating to events in the Revolution and to Rodney's career in the Continental Congress.

abstract: The sixth shooting competition for the Capt. Francis G. abstract: ATLANTA, Ga., April 4. -- The New York Americans completed their Spring training in this section to-day by defeating the Atlanta team, 6 to 5. abstract: PRINCETON, April 4. -- Princeton captured first place in the intercollegiate swimming meet here to-night with a total of 17 points. Yale came second with 15 and Pennsylvania third with 13 points. Two records were smashed. Denniston of Princeton broke his former 30-yard record, made against Richards of Yale last week, covering the distance in 0:26 1-5.

abstract: In this morning's TIMES a letter from William Ryan says that in London all sorts of ideas are discussed at open meetings in Trafalgar Square. I want to say that those meetings are not allowed unless a permit has been issued. In 1887, on Sunday, Nov. 13, I was in London, and in driving to Westminster Abbey passed Trafalgar Square, which had been emptied of people, and which was completely surrounded by mounted police.

abstract: MORRISTOWN, N.J., April 4. -- With the approach of Spring Morristown has taken with enthusiasm to roller skating. abstract: LYNCHBURG, Va., April 5. -- The New York American League team which left Atlanta Saturday midnight, arrived in Lynchburg at 6 o'clock this evening. The Yankees will go to Roanoke for a game to-morrow, returning to Lynchburg for a contest against the local Virginia League, team on Tuesday. Hal Chase left for Richmond to-night to join the second team, which is exhibiting in that city.

abstract: WASHINGTON, April 6. -- A canvass of the House made by Representative Hill of Connecticut discloses the fact that only seventy Republicans, less than one-third that party's membership, favor the passage of the Aldrich bill. It has been known for more than a month that the Senate bill was not popular with Western Republicans, but not until actual canvass was made was the extent of the disaffection known.

abstract: OSSINING, N.Y., April 6. -- Joseph La Sala, serving a sentence of eleven years for highway robbery, has escaped from Sing Sing, and to-night Warden Frost's deputies are searching the prison inside and outside to get some trace of him. La Sala, who was known as Convict No. 13,882, was not an unruly prisoner, but he was known to have boasted that the prison was not strong enough to hold him.

abstract: At the last session of Congress a bill was passed amending and strengthening the statutes relating to naturalization. abstract: LITTLE ROCK, Ark., April 7. -- The regular team of the New York Nationals made playthings of the Little Rock nine of the Southern League to-day, defeating them by a score of 7 to 3. abstract: ALBANY, April 7. -- The inference drawn here from the action of the Senate Finance Committee to-day, in reporting favorably a concurrent resolution providing for final adjournment on April 23, is that leaders of the Governor's own party in the Legislature are determined that all of his reform measures not already passed shall be defeated. abstract: The splendid street display of the self-moving vehicles on Broadway last night has not been equaled anywhere else in the world. There have been motor car parades in plenty; every seaside resort has them nowadays every Summer; but here were thousands of cars in line, representing every type of self-moving vehicle produced in the last ten years, a period that practically comprises the development of the automobile industry in the United States.

abstract: Fifteen hundred frantic men and women, parents of children in the Seventh Avenue public school in Newark, most of whom were Italians, surrounded the building yesterday morning on report of a "Black Hand" threat that the structure was to be destroyed by dynamite. abstract: Jay Gould, Tuxedo Racquet and Tennis Club, must defend his title of amateur court tennis champion of the United States against Eustace H. Miles of England. abstract: The legislative position in respect to the bills prohibiting race-track gambling is that of a deadlock. abstract: WHAT most strikes you, when you come to study the criminal in literature, is the antiquity of the "bad man," either as the hero or the anti-hero. abstract: BUFFALO, N.Y., April 11. -- Gov. Charles E. Hughes celebrated his 48th birthday anniversary to-day as the guest of Buffalo. It was compiled by Hartman Schedel, and printed by Antony Koberger, in Nuremberg, in 1492.

abstract: LOUISVILLE, Ky., April 13. -- Gov. John A. Johnson of Minnesota was formally introduced to-night to the Democrats of Kentucky at the banquet of the Jefferson Club, where he delivered the principal address. abstract: PHILADELPHIA, April 13. -- The will of Thomas B. Wanamaker, disposing of an estate estimated at more than $10,000,000, was probated to-day. abstract: Dealings in securities on the Stock Exchange yesterday dwindled again, a fair measure of the dullness of the trading being found in the fact that there were no transactions at all in so conspicuous a stock as New York Central. abstract: The Thomas car, leader in the New York to Paris race, is due to return to Seattle to-day from Valdez on the steamer Jennie, after having tried the Alaskan trail and found it impassable. abstract: ELIZABETH CITY, N.C., April 17. -- The steam yacht Kemah of New York arrived at this port at 4 o'clock this afternoon, disabled. The yacht was coming through Croatan Sound yesterday morning when a heavy north gale struck her, carrying away both her masts. The crew was compelled to cut away the broken parts and gear to save the yacht from driving ashore.

abstract: Mr. STANCHFIELD perhaps expressed a general sentiment when he stated that Directors of corporations have a right to profit in the market by information gained in their Directorial capacity. Nevertheless it is a sentiment which is essentially immoral and which should be checked if it in fact exists. That a Director can be a competitive buyer in the market of a stock which his company also wishes to buy is incompatible with good conscience.

abstract: Few people who order a planked steak or fish in a Broadway restaurant realize that they are returning, as it were, to nature. For while the juicy steak on a grooved board, surrounded by artistically arranged vegetables and garnishing represents the high skill of the modern chef, the idea of cooking on a board originated with the negroes of the South, who invented this method simply because they had no iron pans or broilers.

abstract: CAMBRIDGE, Mass., April 18. -- Fordham walloped the Harvard nine at baseball this afternoon on Soldiers' Field, 9 to 7. abstract: TIFLIS, April 18. -- Lieut. Gen. abstract: FORT WORTH, Texas, April 18. -- Another rise of three feet in the Clear and West forks, following the cloudburst last night, forced thousands of persons to flee from their homes in East Fort Worth to-day. abstract: ITHACA, N.Y., April 18. -- In a drizzling rain this afternoon Cornell defeated New York University by the score of 11 to 8. The game was very loosely played on account of the wet weather, and runs were made in bunches. New York led until the seventh, when Cornell piled up five runs. Goish was wild and hit five men. Gable pitched an excellent game, except in one inning.

abstract: The home of Emanuel Bloomingdale, a lawyer, a member of the firm of Bloomingdale Brothers, owners of the department store at Fifty-ninth Street and Third Avenue, was entered by two burglars last night and robbed of considerable jewelry. The house is at 42 West Sixty-ninth Street. Most of the stolen property consisted of presents Mrs. Bloomingdale had received since she was a small child, and was made up of rings, pins, chains, and bracelets.

abstract: PHILADELPHIA, April 19. -- The motive which drove the Rev. George W. Tomson, pastor of the Woodbury Presbyterian Church, to end his life was revealed to-day. Fearing that a faction of his congregation planned to prefer charges of unbecoming conduct against him at the session of the church, Mr. Tomson tallied himself, preferring death to an airing of a scandal in which the names of several Woodbury and Clayton women would be linked with his.

abstract: LOS ANGELES, Cal., April 19. -- Tonight, for the first time since leaving Hampton Roads, the battleships of the Atlantic fleet are separated. abstract: ALBANY, April 20. -- Fire risks aggregating $5,440,407,457 were written by fire insurance companies in the State in 1907, according to the report of Superintendent of Insurance Kelsey. abstract: Forty-one debutantes attired like "La Belle Chocolatiere," which hangs in the Dresden Gallery, took part in an entertainment in the ballroom of the Plaza yesterday afternoon. More than $3,000 was cleared, it was said, which is to go toward the support of free beds for consumptive children in the Loomis Sanitarium.

abstract: CLEVELAND, April 22. -- Chicago defeated Cleveland to-day by the score of 4 to 0. Liebhardt, who started for Cleveland, was ineffective, but Rhoades, who succeeded him, pitched a strong game. Owen was a puzzle to the locals and held them to three hits. Throws to the plate by Birmingham and Hinchman, completing double plays, were features.

abstract: We regret to note in the comments of some of our contemporaries a flippant or ironical tone touching the announcements of a farewell tour of Mme. ADELINA PATTI. abstract: LAKEWOOD, N.J., April 23. -- Fred Herreshoff of New York to-day easily captured the low-score prize in the annual Spring golf tourney of the Country Club of Lakewood in the thirty-six-hole qualifying round. He was six strokes better than W.H. Davis of Lakewood, Howard Whitney of Nassau being third, ten strokes higher than Herreshoff. Findlay Douglas, ex-National champion, was eighth in the field of sixty-seven starters, all but one of whom finished.

abstract: LATTINGTOWN, L.I., April 23. -- About 2 o'clock this afternoon a maid in the household of Paul D. Cravath, at Locust Valley, discovered a small blaze in the kitchen dumbwaiter. Three hours later Verator, the beautiful Cravath country home, was a mass of smoldering ruins. Mrs. Cravath and little Miss Cravath have not come from the city, and the only occupants of the house were a housekeeper and four maids.

abstract: NEWARK, April 23. -- There was a lively mix-up between Manager George Stallings of the Newark Club and Umpire Sullivan after the game between Newark and Buffalo this afternoon. When Sullivan went to the dressing room Stallings proceeded to tell him what he thought of his umpiring. As Sullivan had heard the same thing from the spectators many times during the game, he did not relish it and retorted.

abstract: ELIZABETH, N.J., April 23. -- Representative Charles N. Fowler defended his currency views in an address before the Republican Club here to-night, saying that in 1873 one man, President Grant, was wiser than the whole Republican Congress when he vetoed the Greenback bill. Hayes was above his party in 1878, he said, when he vetoed another Greenback bill, and Cleveland was wiser than the Democratic Party in 1893 when he disapproved a free silver measure.

abstract: Mme. Vera Komisarzhevsky leaves New York next Tuesday on the Kaiser Wilhelm II. Her company, after a tearful parting with the Countess at the Everett House, sailed yesterday on the French liner Touraine. The Countess, who remains to visit Niagara Falls, spoke of the unfavorable impressions she had received of this country, but said that she might possibly return some time, though not again under Russian management.

abstract: In your editorial reference to the death of Mr. Chadwick you state that the first professional baseball club was the Cincinnati Red Stockings, organized in 1868. You are in error. abstract: LONDON, April 24. -- Not within the memory of the present generation has Great Britain been visited by such furious blizzards so late in the Spring as began to rage throughout the whole country on Thursday and continued early to-day. abstract: One is inclined to feel regretful over Neith Boyle's novel, "The Bond." (Duffield and Co.) It is not at all a bad novel. abstract: WASHINGTON, April 25. -- Since the last summary of the Republican Presidential situation there have been elected fifty-two delegates to the Chicago Convention. abstract: PARIS, April 25. -- The widowed Duchesse de Chaulnes, formerly Miss Theodora Shonts of New York, this afternoon went to the Chateau Dampierre, the ancestral residence of the Luynes family outside Paris. abstract: The growth of the Catholic Church in the United States coincides with the growth of the country. abstract: Congress faces a change for the worse in National finances of something like $120,000,000. That is to say, the surplus, in round numbers, of $55,000,000 will by the close of June be turned into a deficit of $65,000,000. Despite the fact that there is a balance of cash on hand and in bank approaching $250,000,000, this is not a comfortable or cheerful situation.

abstract: MOBILE, Ala., April 25. -- All records at moving targets were broken at Fort Morgan yesterday in the target practice with the big twelve-inch guns. The practice was by the members of the Seventy-fifth Company of Artillery. Nine shots were fired by the gunners in the twelve minutes, six of the shots were fired in two minutes and forty-five seconds, which is also a new record for seacoast artillery gunners.

abstract: BOSTON, April 27. -- This was something like Glad Hand Day in the Boston baseball park. abstract: Stockholders of the Westinghouse Electric and Manufacturing Company were in receipt of a circular yesterday from President George Westinghouse, urging them to participate in the readjustment plan formulated by the Merchandise Creditors' Committee early this month. Mr. Westinghouse calls attention to the better position of the company at this time.

abstract: Forty more policemen, who helped guard the ballot boxes holding the votes of the Mayoralty election in 1905, were examined in the Hearst-McClellan recount case yesterday, and when the court adjourned the Bronx police were being rapidly examined. Counsel for the Attorney General hope to start with the Kings police to-day.
